commit_message:
Add Networking-L2GW project

This repo will be used for the development of L2 Gateways initiatives
that integrate with Neutron.

In line with proposal [1], and as suggested in [2], this project will be
used to achieve loose coupling with Neutron, and to allow contributors to
experiment outside the core of the Neutron project.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/136835/
[2] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron-drivers

Change-Id: I5f4099a9613f82e7ba7e9478ea93dd5816c3cbc5

net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-iptables = 1
net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-ip6tables = 1

Otherwise security groups functionality may be broken after

"}]
commit_message:
Fix sysctl settings for neutron on CentOS

We should make sure the following settings are configured
/etc/sysctl.conf file on compute nodes in case we use neutron:

net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-arptables = 1
net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-iptables = 1
net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-ip6tables = 1

Otherwise security groups functionality may be broken after
executing 'sysctl -p' on compute nodes.

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1400787
Change-Id: I8582c24706c3a7253e00569eef275f116d765bca

commit_message:
Mapping enhancements - direct groups mapping.

This specification proposes changes in the mapping engine logic,
allowing for direct groups mapping passed in a assertion/claim.
Part of the implementation included alowing for identification local groups with name/domain. 

Change-Id: Ibe1e838abd050c30cf38478dfcf1580c65bcc344

commit_message:
move maxconn from each backend to the overall configuration

controlling the number of connection for each backend is not enough
and won't work if the number is bigger than default maxconn,
which takes precedence for overall frontend and backend session limit,
so move the maxconn for each service to the overall configuration
instead of a particular backend node.

Change-Id: I971d93eab7424639a0fb5f0705f94ac9c6931044

This change is part of a multi-part change set to handle obsolete and
graduated oslo modules. This commit handles the network_utils module
which is now oslo.utils.netutils.

commit_message:
Add method for getting the CPU pinning constraint

We add nova.virt.hardware.numa_cpu_pinning_get_constraint method that
given the flavor, image, and an already decided NUMA topology, will add
the CPU pinning information to the topology (or create a single cell
topology as we currently don't do it if no topology was requested to
minimize the DB footprint and thus the amount of data that needs to flow
around).

Once we make sure this is call while building the instance data in the
API, this data will later be used in the scheduling.

Change-Id: I382738a6b255b21cd00c1d9d049f69f7d784d653
Blueprint: virt-driver-cpu-pinning

commit_message:
Remove duplicate dependencies from dev-quickstart docs

Turns out certain versions of Ubuntu packages tox to use Python
3, which breaks installing MySQL-Python into 2.x virtualenvs.
Since we already have "pip install tox" in these docs, let's
stick with that method rather than depending on what distros do.

Also remove other packages from SUSE line that are
duplicated by the "pip install" line.

Change-Id: I472704ab879446586ec7fa7ecd79da4f7212b81d
Closes-Bug: 1399463

commit_message:
Configure boto.cfg in tempest to point to SSL bundle

The boto client uses the ca_certificate_files value in the
Boto section of /etc/boto.cfg when making an SSL client
connection. Configure that to be the devstack SSL CA bundle
so the boto tests will pass when running against an SSL or
TLS-proxy configured devstack environment.

Change-Id: I55ae6d6e0c5b3adb4370ec93f40ae1cd47741457

[{'number': 3, 'created': '2014-11-18 21:05:56.000000000', 'files': ['lib/ceph'], 'message': 'Fix the variable substitution

Prior to that commit if ceph_version was equal to 0.80.5, the variable
substitution ${ceph_version%.*} was returning 0.80 and not 0. Using
${ceph_version%%.*} returns the desired value.
Also refactoring the version output to get a X.X format since only
major and minor are important.

commit_message:
Fix the variable substitution

Prior to that commit if ceph_version was equal to 0.80.5, the variable
substitution ${ceph_version%.*} was returning 0.80 and not 0. Using
${ceph_version%%.*} returns the desired value.
Also refactoring the version output to get a X.X format since only
major and minor are important.

Change-Id: Iab50f3c4b24a01a68acda417eae0501f00038f54
Signed-off-by: Sébastien Han <sebastien.han@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Move ironic ssh key creation early in preparation

SSH creds should be in place before nodes are enrolled.  If not,
ironic cannot sync power state causing nova to skip nodes in
its resource tracker.

Change-Id: I6b98ae57ce33783f69e2cf9ba357807d384b3012
Closes-bug: #1398128

commit_message:
Do not regenerate ironic ssh key if one exists

Gets rid of redundant globals and avoids regenerating an ssh key
for ironic if one exists.  Also allows key file to be user-specified,
letting ironic use pregenerated keys.

Change-Id: Iaa6f8918bf14dae2116269a0be5039fc5afaecfa

The current parsing of the interfaces from the neutron network namespace
fails if there are other things that match 'tap' (ie, gretaps created
for other purposes)  This tightens up the parsing to only match devices

commit_message:
Tighten up parsing of neutron tap device for ironic

The current parsing of the interfaces from the neutron network namespace
fails if there are other things that match 'tap' (ie, gretaps created
for other purposes)  This tightens up the parsing to only match devices
starting 'tap' instead of anything containing 'tap'

Change-Id: I9a31ec8ad253da0b3c5bd7f5eb105c49850f3060

Add cinder stress scenario: nested snapshots

This scenario creates volumes and snapshots chain with custom nested
level:
1. Create volume
2. Create snapshot
3. Create volume from snapshot
... and so on

commit_message:
Don't create extra nodes if nodes file is provided

Unless NODE_CNT is pre-set, we default to creating 15 new nodes, even if
--nodes is used to point at a set of existing nodes. This requires
prebuilt environments to be created by passing --nodes *AND* setting
NODE_CNT to -1

This change makes it easier to use a prebuilt environment; if --nodes is
supplied, NODE_CNT will default to 0 - but an external setting will
still be observed.

It's possible that this change is rendered moot by other work that is
happening to seperate the bm network and node manipulation from the
create-a-test-env portions of the script.

Change-Id: I0291ba5b83ab0ffce7ea7f9e956ee1c1db88bc5b

commit_message:
Consider invalid keywords a template validation error

This commit changes the exception type raised when an invalid
keyword is found in the resources and outputs sections of hot
templates from a KeyError to a StackValidationFailed. The
latter is better suited to be sent to heat-api to return to
clients, as oslo.messaging deserializes it to a more compact
exception that does not include the stack trace in the message
string.

Change-Id: I7c2da96fa07503b947c6c2c4a5f8ed3231dec9db
Closes-Bug: 1393831

This proposal adds Role Based Access Control for the Ceilometer

the specific methods that a user can call. For instance it
would be possible to have only users with special roles in
creating or deleting alarms whilst all the users can verify

A policy.json file will contain the specific rules to apply

commit_message:
Ceilometer RBAC Support for API

This proposal adds Role Based Access Control for the Ceilometer
API. Using RBAC is possible to restrict/enforce limitations in
the specific methods that a user can call. For instance it
would be possible to have only users with special roles in
creating or deleting alarms whilst all the users can verify
them.

A policy.json file will contain the specific rules to apply
for the different roles leaving to the deployer the ability
of enforcing specific restrictions without having to change
the implementation.

Co-Authored-By: Fabio Giannetti <fabio.giannetti@hp.com>

Change-Id: I965a5dc2143b89018b7bdfe48db440e35b749b6a

commit_message:
Horizon login page contains DOS attack mechanism

the horizon login page (really the middleware) accesses the session
too early in the login process, which will create session records
in the session backend.  This is especially problematic when non-cookie
backends are used.

Change-Id: I9d2c40403fb9b0cfb512f2ff45397cbe0b050c71
Closes-Bug: 1394370

commit_message:
Horizon login page contains DOS attack mechanism

the horizon login page (and middleware) accesses the session
too early in the login process, which will create session records
in the session backend.  This is especially problematic when non-cookie
backends are used.

subject: Removes username and password support from RHEL registration
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 7144, 'name': 'James Slagle', 'email': 'jslagle@redhat.com', 'username': 'slagle'}, {'_account_id': 8532, 'name': 'Ryan Brady', 'email': 'rbrady@redhat.com', 'username': 'rbrady'}, {'_account_id': 12092, 'name': 'Abel Lopez', 'email': 'abelopez@cisco.com', 'username': 'alopgeek'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-12-05 19:54:19.000000000', 'files': ['elements/rhel-common/README.md', 'elements/rhel-common/os-refresh-config/pre-configure.d/06-rhel-registration', 'elements/rhel-common/pre-install.d/00-rhel-registration'], 'message': 'Removes username and password support from RHEL registration

The username and password combination is considered insecure to store in
the metadata passed to the stack as they can easily be obtained and
possibly used in an unathorized manner by logging into one of the
registration systems. The use of an activation key is more desirable
as it can only be used in conjunction with subscription-manager to
register a RHEL system.

This patch removes the username and password support from the scripts
that register RHEL with either Satellite or RH Customer Portal.  This
patch also adds a warning if an activation key is not present in the
stack metadata and an error if the activation key is not present in
REG_ACTIVATION_KEY.  The documentation and examples have also been
updated to remove any mention of username and password.

Change-Id: I5a8d00431e3eea5f476a51b1394771bd7258e08b
'}]
commit_message:
Removes username and password support from RHEL registration

The username and password combination is considered insecure to store in
the metadata passed to the stack as they can easily be obtained and
possibly used in an unathorized manner by logging into one of the
registration systems. The use of an activation key is more desirable
as it can only be used in conjunction with subscription-manager to
register a RHEL system.

This patch removes the username and password support from the scripts
that register RHEL with either Satellite or RH Customer Portal.  This
patch also adds a warning if an activation key is not present in the
stack metadata and an error if the activation key is not present in
REG_ACTIVATION_KEY.  The documentation and examples have also been
updated to remove any mention of username and password.

Change-Id: I5a8d00431e3eea5f476a51b1394771bd7258e08b

commit_message:
Horizon login page contains DOS attack mechanism

the horizon login page (really the middleware) accesses the session
too early in the login process, which will create session records
in the session backend.  This is especially problematic when non-cookie
backends are used.

Change-Id: I7b06908642fb1469f040e195f6730b5c63221b4d
Closes-Bug: 1394370

Designate and Sahara erroneously used the publish-to-pypi template.
It was convenient to generate tarballs on pre-release and release
tags, but it also resulted in a server tarball upload to PyPi,
which is not something we do for server projects. This commit
removes the extra jobs before we push the kilo-1 milestone.

Barbican and Zaqar did not use the merge-release-tags job, while
they probably should. Aligning them will allow to let all integrated

'}]
commit_message:
Fix release publication for server projects

Designate and Sahara erroneously used the publish-to-pypi template.
It was convenient to generate tarballs on pre-release and release
tags, but it also resulted in a server tarball upload to PyPi,
which is not something we do for server projects. This commit
removes the extra jobs before we push the kilo-1 milestone.

Barbican and Zaqar did not use the merge-release-tags job, while
they probably should. Aligning them will allow to let all integrated
and incubated server projects use the same job template (proposed in
a subsequent commit).

Change-Id: Id46e00a05b2c943b51469f948b1d152f09be35f2

commit_message:
Fix system test vcenter_vmdk

There is ostf test 'Launch instance, create snapshot, launch instance from
snapshot' which never works in Fuel 5.x with vCenter hypervisor due to 
timeout problem. And in system test vcenter_vmdk it was marked as 
'should fail'.

Now problem with timeouts solved and mark 'should fail' must be canceled.

Change-Id: I2ed6c9359fd58ab37133bab133569273c9084a54
Closes-bug: 1400287

commit_message:
Remote file import for already existing image

Current task mechanism supports only creation of new
images, however in v2 when image already exists we have
to use image-upload api call, which works only with local
files and doesn't support execution in the background.

Here the code that extends import task mechanism with
the ability to import file for already existing image by
providing image_id in task input parameters.

Change-Id: Ia30c45e4bd99246fd52e876b5eaefe8f21479ca4

commit_message:
Remote file import for already existing image

Current task mechanism supports only creation of new
images, however in v2 when image already exists we have
to use image-upload api call, which works only with local
files and doesn't support execution in the background. It
is suggested to extend task mechanism with the ability to
import file for already existing image.

Change-Id: Ia644ad2b0750b70276834ff048cd670d9417afde

commit_message:
Fix libxslt-dev reference

The libxslt package on Ubuntu is actually named libxslt1-dev, but it
provised the libxslt-dev package.  This means that each time puppet
runs, it looks for, doesn't find and reinstalls libxslt-dev, which
actually installs libxslt1-dev.

Change-Id: Ibd21d70605ab98a569e7abae654d0463672b7b37

commit_message:
Ensure extension aliases are used for nova based services

This commit fixes the extension checker in verify-tempest-config to
ensure that nova and nova based services are using the extension
aliases instead of the extension names. The extension names are meant
to be human readable and are not the best way to identify it. This is
what the tempest code is also expecting, however in some cases the
name was still being used by the verify tool, which was incorrect. As
part of this it was necessary to fix several other places where name
was being used instead of alias, or other extension list formatting
response checking was incorrect.

Change-Id: I35f5db655f065f29760515a26db1fb508d229393

commit_message:
Add more verbose info for wait_for_..._status methods

If this method failed because the resource will not reach desired
status, you just know expected status, not actual status at time of
timeout. It can help with debugging.

commit_message:
Port to graduated library oslo.i18n

log_handler is not used any more by Ceilometer project, but still
listed on openstack-common.conf, this patch fixes it.

Note: oslo-incubator.timeutils is not used by oslo-incubator modules
any more after we do code sync, this patch removes it too.

gettextutils has graduated from oslo-incubator, we should port our
project to use oslo.i18n. To use oslo.i18n conveniently, this patch
introduces a helper module ceilometer.i18n, which is stolen from Nova.

Note: gettextutils.install is deprecated, see:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/usage.html#creating-an-integration-module
Note: _ is removed from builtins in tox.ini since we're not using
install any more.

Change-Id: I829f9faf97c825422b395bf9c01ae5c17c86d9fb
Closes-Bug: #1389546

commit_message:
Associate flavor types with datastore versions

This feature provides the ability to associate flavor
types with datastore versions.The trove-mange util enables
adding/deleting this information.The trove-client has been
changed to include a new api call:
/{tenant_id}/datastores/{datastore}/versions/{version}/flavors.
This call will return all nova flavors if no entries are found
for the said datastore-version in datastore_version_metadata,
otherwise only the entries found are returned.

Change-Id: I89fc2db0078d7884b7b3fa91f5daec68c0132dfb
Implements: blueprint associate-flavors-datastores

revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2014-12-09 07:17:18.000000000', 'files': ['mistral/engine1/commands.py', 'mistral/tests/unit/engine1/test_join.py'], 'message': 'Working on "join": fixing "partial join" test new "noop" engine command

* "noop" command is needed in this test to have a deterministic behavior
  regarding the last task in the workflow. Previously, there was a
  uncertainty wether task4 or task5 was going to run last and we couldn't
  reliably calculate workflow output. One more interesting thing: task5
  was added as a "no operation dead end" for task3 only. So it seemed to
  make perfect sense to avoid adding a whole task and just add a new
  no operation command instead.

Change-Id: Ie5d8861f289cb43bc383d0b617a95ae43185c86d
'}]
commit_message:
Working on "join": fixing "partial join" test new "noop" engine command

* "noop" command is needed in this test to have a deterministic behavior
  regarding the last task in the workflow. Previously, there was a
  uncertainty wether task4 or task5 was going to run last and we couldn't
  reliably calculate workflow output. One more interesting thing: task5
  was added as a "no operation dead end" for task3 only. So it seemed to
  make perfect sense to avoid adding a whole task and just add a new
  no operation command instead.

Modal fixes - 2 columns, padding, header, membership

Adds padding to tab-content which takes care of proper
spacing between tabs and tab-content.
refactors tabs styling - match modal and non-modal tabs
Changes modal header h3 margin to save space.

Changes create and update image modal template as an example.
The rest of the views is changed in subsequent patch

subject: Re-build dependencies for custom add_dependencies
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 4257, 'name': 'Zane Bitter', 'email': 'zbitter@redhat.com', 'username': 'zaneb'}, {'_account_id': 6577, 'name': 'Sergey Kraynev', 'email': 'sergejyit@gmail.com', 'username': 'skraynev'}, {'_account_id': 13009, 'name': 'Peter Razumovsky', 'email': 'prazumovsky@mirantis.com', 'username': 'prazumovsky'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2014-12-05 12:24:22.000000000', 'files': ['heat/engine/stack.py', 'heat/tests/test_neutron.py'], 'message': 'Re-build dependencies for custom add_dependencies

Some Heat resources have their own add_dependencies method, which uses
dependency graph. In rare cases, when we call _get_dependecies method of
stack resource, such resources may be first in the resources list.
It leads in situation when dependencies is empty and we lose some
custom dependencies.
This patch adds additional cycle, which allows to avoid such situation.
On the second loop iteration graph will stay same and will be only added
custom dependecy (such for FloatingIP resource).

Closes-Bug: #1299259

Change-Id: I1e2a00d89a0940e447a48367159308f497bb91fb
'}]
commit_message:
Re-build dependencies for custom add_dependencies

Some Heat resources have their own add_dependencies method, which uses
dependency graph. In rare cases, when we call _get_dependecies method of
stack resource, such resources may be first in the resources list.
It leads in situation when dependencies is empty and we lose some
custom dependencies.
This patch adds additional cycle, which allows to avoid such situation.
On the second loop iteration graph will stay same and will be only added
custom dependecy (such for FloatingIP resource).

Closes-Bug: #1299259

Change-Id: I1e2a00d89a0940e447a48367159308f497bb91fb

commit_message:
wrong message while deleting non empty pseudo folder

while try to delete a pseudo folder which contains some objects is
showing the success message but the folder is not actually deleted

added a check similar to delete container, the new check will
verify the pseudo folder is empty before call the swift client
call. if the folder is not empty it will throw a exception
with a appropriate error message and the message will be shown to
the user in the pop up message box.

Change-Id: I0bbea6ef6ac26ef357240610535b9d84053a89c2
Closes-Bug: #1347598

commit_message:
Update non-issues section of 5.1.1 Release Notes

Adds link to latest Icehouse Release Notes
refreshes update/upgrade info for 5.1.1
adds note that Fuel Access Control is enhanced
Also updates dates and release numbers for the set

NSX support is now marked as Experimental in "New Features"
terminology/experimental updated to list NSX as experimental

Note that the descriptive "What is Mirantis OpenStack" material
remains in the Release Notes for 5.1.1;
it will be moved to the docs landing page for 6.0.

Resolved and Known Issues are being worked in separate Commits.

Change-Id: Ic6a1f39aa3ae52e097e445f5635c4ffa293ab537

commit_message:
5.1.1 update to authorization feature

Document updates to Fuel Authorization being implemented in 5.1.1.
This is similar to 6.0 implementation, but the following changes
are not implemented in 5.1.1:
- keystonemiddleware
- Nailgun and OSTF services endpoints in Keystone
- nailgun and ostf users in services project
- authentication token that does not expire for 24 hours

operations: update 6500-fuel-auth with info about new features

user-guide:
- Add --password option for fuel CLI
- 8000-upgrade is xref'ed from this commit but the instructions
  to supply the password are NOT in this commit; they are in the
  upgrade commit for smoother reviewing.

terminology/Keystone -- an instance of Keystone runs in a container now
in addition to the instances that run on the target nodes.

Change-Id: I355afa66f12deee46f6c05337d137d1703227134
Partial-Bug: 1384343
Partial-Bug: 1387667
Partial-Bug: 1392626
Closes-Bug: 1392289

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-12-08 17:16:30.000000000', 'files': ['cinder/tests/test_nfs.py', 'cinder/volume/drivers/nfs.py'], 'message': "Fixes intermittent NFS driver mount failure

During cinder volume driver initialization, NFS drivers often
fail to mount the NFS share backing their volumes, complaining
that the share in question is 'busy or already mounted'.

This commit introduces a retry loop around the ensure_mounted()
call inside set_nas_security_options() so that if there is contention
between volume process and backup process mounting the same share
the driver will not be stopped from loading.

Change-Id: I672433c1c31f420e5dcdbe565db3bb29af3abe7b
Closes-bug: 1395823
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes intermittent NFS driver mount failure

During cinder volume driver initialization, NFS drivers often
fail to mount the NFS share backing their volumes, complaining
that the share in question is 'busy or already mounted'.

This commit introduces a retry loop around the ensure_mounted()
call inside set_nas_security_options() so that if there is contention
between volume process and backup process mounting the same share
the driver will not be stopped from loading.

Change-Id: I672433c1c31f420e5dcdbe565db3bb29af3abe7b
Closes-bug: 1395823

commit_message:
Replace assertEqual(*, True/False) with assertTrue/False(*)

The following replacements were done in tests to have
clearer messages in case of failure:
- assertEqual(*, True) with assertTrue(*)
- assertEqual(*, False) with assertFalse(*)
- assertEqual(True, *) with assertTrue(*)
- assertEqual(False, *) with assertFalse(*)

Change-Id: Ib19b06520e82e8cd9d32f2c3b168e1b8051cdd0d

commit_message:
Remove dsvm-cells tests from places they don't do anything

The dsvm-cells tests only run exercises, and basically only test that
1 guest boots with a volume. They aren't relevant to horizon, heat, or
keystone as there isn't sufficiently high probability that changes
there can impact the success of this test.

Change-Id: I9b9d65f3bb02283542bcde0d95f6e79eeb0bd23d

parameters set (otherwise theres really no point to log levels at all).
Therefore we should have our example configs turn debug and verbose off.

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 1297, 'name': 'Joshua Harlow', 'email': 'jxharlow@godaddy.com', 'username': 'harlowja'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2014-12-06 23:04:26.000000000', 'files': ['taskflow/tests/unit/worker_based/test_protocol.py', 'taskflow/tests/unit/worker_based/test_pipeline.py', 'taskflow/engines/action_engine/actions/retry.py', 'taskflow/engines/worker_based/endpoint.py', 'taskflow/engines/action_engine/executor.py', 'taskflow/engines/action_engine/runner.py', 'taskflow/engines/worker_based/protocol.py'], 'message': 'Stop returning atoms from execute/revert methods

It is not needed to return the atom that was executed from the
futures result() method, since we can just as easily set an
attribute on the future and reference it from there when using
it later. This is also required for a process based executor since
it is not typically possible to send back a raw task object (and
is not desireable to require this); even if it was possible the
task would be pickled and unpickled multiple times so when this
happens it can not be guaranteed to even be the same object (in
fact it is not).

Part of blueprint process-executor

Change-Id: I4a05ea5dcdef97218312e3a88ed4a1dfdf1b1edf
'}]
commit_message:
Stop returning atoms from execute/revert methods

It is not needed to return the atom that was executed from the
futures result() method, since we can just as easily set an
attribute on the future and reference it from there when using
it later. This is also required for a process based executor since
it is not typically possible to send back a raw task object (and
is not desireable to require this); even if it was possible the
task would be pickled and unpickled multiple times so when this
happens it can not be guaranteed to even be the same object (in
fact it is not).

Part of blueprint process-executor

Change-Id: I4a05ea5dcdef97218312e3a88ed4a1dfdf1b1edf

commit_message:
Use an appropriate ``extract_traceback`` limit

When looking for where this modules ``run/load`` ends and
the user code begins we only need to search back at most
three levels to find this information; so to avoid getting
many more frames (especially when they won't be used) then
we need to just apply a sensible limit on the levels we get.

Change-Id: I9186e8844c92697b7e3f850328b6b39afba0150d

commit_message:
Don't use lsb_release

Using lsb_release to figure out what distro and release an image is
is redundant, as the same information is available in DIB_ vars.
Further, it causes errors when creating new rhel7/centos7 images
like this: http://paste.openstack.org/show/144729/

Change-Id: I213ee581b8abfe119ffe3b783e6a3236e58e3e47

subject: Have tasks be able to provide copy() methods
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 1297, 'name': 'Joshua Harlow', 'email': 'jxharlow@godaddy.com', 'username': 'harlowja'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2014-12-06 22:46:45.000000000', 'files': ['taskflow/task.py', 'taskflow/tests/unit/test_task.py'], 'message': 'Have tasks be able to provide copy() methods

When a engine needs to copy a task and possibly
adjust its listeners to execute it elsewhere it
needs to be able to clone that object and have
the clone retain different properties than the
initial object; so in order to support this at
a top-level we require a new copy() method which
a task can override (or it can just use the default
implementation if it chooses to).

Part of blueprint process-executor

Change-Id: Ib29a0afdc01973eb94d41af18a9b04601cd2f152
'}]
commit_message:
Have tasks be able to provide copy() methods

When a engine needs to copy a task and possibly
adjust its listeners to execute it elsewhere it
needs to be able to clone that object and have
the clone retain different properties than the
initial object; so in order to support this at
a top-level we require a new copy() method which
a task can override (or it can just use the default
implementation if it chooses to).

Part of blueprint process-executor

Change-Id: Ib29a0afdc01973eb94d41af18a9b04601cd2f152

commit_message:
Allow stopwatches to be restarted

It is quite useful to allow a stopwatch to be reset
or restarted in a single operation, instead of having
to handle this logic outside of the stopwatch object,
which is error-prone and unnecessary to require users
to reinvent.

Part of blueprint process-executor

commit_message:
Ensure that failures can be pickled

When a failure happens in a subprocess it needs to be
pickleable (and not contain a traceback, since those can
not be pickled) when being sent across the process boundary
so that the receiving process can read it and unpickle
the corresponding object.

Part of blueprint process-executor

Change-Id: I2f26faa4e02da6acf4f0840239d0b17143de8d76

subject: Rework pieces of the task callback capability
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 1297, 'name': 'Joshua Harlow', 'email': 'jxharlow@godaddy.com', 'username': 'harlowja'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2014-12-06 22:29:43.000000000', 'files': ['taskflow/task.py', 'taskflow/engines/action_engine/executor.py', 'taskflow/tests/unit/test_task.py'], 'message': "Rework pieces of the task callback capability

Unifies the bind, unbind, autobind parameters.

Also to make it easier to introspect what are a tasks associated
callbacks and events are provide a listeners_iter() method that
can be used to introspect the registered (event, callbacks) pairs that
are registered with a task.

Also adds more useful docstrings to the various callback associated
binding, unbinding functions to make it more understandable how they
are used and what they are provided.

Also makes the currently only default provided event 'update_progress'
a constant that can be referenced from the task module, which allows others
to easily find it and use it.

Change-Id: I14181a150b74fbd97f6ea976723f37c0ba4cec36
"}]
commit_message:
Rework pieces of the task callback capability

Unifies the bind, unbind, autobind parameters.

Also to make it easier to introspect what are a tasks associated
callbacks and events are provide a listeners_iter() method that
can be used to introspect the registered (event, callbacks) pairs that
are registered with a task.

Also adds more useful docstrings to the various callback associated
binding, unbinding functions to make it more understandable how they
are used and what they are provided.

Also makes the currently only default provided event 'update_progress'
a constant that can be referenced from the task module, which allows others
to easily find it and use it.

Change-Id: I14181a150b74fbd97f6ea976723f37c0ba4cec36

revisions:
[{'number': 14, 'created': '2014-12-02 22:36:14.000000000', 'files': ['specs/kilo/vsphere-neutron.rst'], 'message': "Umbrella spec for VMware/Neutron support

This spec captures all the available options for OpenStack Networking
when using the VMware vSphere suite in all its shapes and forms.

The aim here is to give the cloud operator/whoever interested in solving
his/her IT needs with OpenStack a framework with which he/she can look at
all the available solutions, what they are/are not, can/cannot do etc. so
that an informed decision can be made without the hassle of inspecting the
code and/or rummaging through the web in order to find answers about what
Neutron's capabilities are wrt VMware vSphere.

In other words, it is the impartial reference for people to go look when
they want to learn about this topic.

This supports efforts for blueprint vsphere-neutron

Change-Id: I131f1b3091866a6f2266d3ddef3b727ee7c961f2
"}]
commit_message:
Umbrella spec for VMware/Neutron support

This spec captures all the available options for OpenStack Networking
when using the VMware vSphere suite in all its shapes and forms.

The aim here is to give the cloud operator/whoever interested in solving
his/her IT needs with OpenStack a framework with which he/she can look at
all the available solutions, what they are/are not, can/cannot do etc. so
that an informed decision can be made without the hassle of inspecting the
code and/or rummaging through the web in order to find answers about what
Neutron's capabilities are wrt VMware vSphere.

In other words, it is the impartial reference for people to go look when
they want to learn about this topic.

This supports efforts for blueprint vsphere-neutron

Change-Id: I131f1b3091866a6f2266d3ddef3b727ee7c961f2

commit_message:
Port oslo.config.generator to automatically generate trove conf files

The general procedure is:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.config/generator.html

The generator entry I defined as follows:
[entry_points]
oslo.config.opts =
    trove.common = trove.common.cfg:list_log_opts
    trove.main = trove.common.cfg:list_opts

The configuration files are created via:
oslo-config-generator --namespace trove.common --namespace trove.main > trove.conf.sample
oslo-config-generator --namespace trove.common > trove-conductor.conf.sample
oslo-config-generator --namespace trove.common > trove-guestagent.conf.sample
oslo-config-generator --namespace trove.common > trove-taskmanager.conf.sample

Change-Id: I5e02b16c91c4203b6c41bf091db97dc77dcb69ea
Closes-Bug: #1234338

commit_message:
Create zuul_swift_upload publishers

Use postbuildscript publishers to capture jobs that have failed
by ensuring that logs are uploaded even if the build has exited.

Keep the build macros as the postbuildscript needs builders to
execute and they also aren't strictly just for use as a publisher.

Change-Id: I21463f89281911dff6efda31e754bdc7b3266e24

commit_message:
Refactor code structure for notification

Given we are going to implement notification, so the 'queues'
package is not suitable for current scope of zaqar. This

commit_message:
Ironic: Remove few misguided negative tests on ports

As part of https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic/+bug/1398350 Ironic is fixing
a bug where the josn-fields in the resources only accepted string and
int, as part of the work Ironic will now support any json serializable
value on those fields.

Some negative tests on ports were considering float to be a malformed
value, which they are not. This patch is removing those tests.

This patch is also adding tests checking for the new supported values
in the API.

The patch in Ironic adding support for multiple types is this one:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/137762/

Change-Id: I02e95d77a90b3c1a8e203cf83cc0ec28b5460e58

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-12-08 14:13:58.000000000', 'files': ['ironic/drivers/modules/agent.py', 'ironic/tests/drivers/test_agent.py'], 'message': "Fix image_info passed to IPA for image download

It's possible to specify instance_info['image_source'] to be a value
like 'glance://uuid'. When using AgentDeploy, image_source is passed
to IPA in image_info dictionary in 'id' field without modification,
and IPA tries to download image to /tmp/{id} location. Deployment
fails as /tmp/glance://uuid is invalid location.

In this change image_source is split to ensure that uuid will be used

"}]
commit_message:
Fix image_info passed to IPA for image download

It's possible to specify instance_info['image_source'] to be a value
like 'glance://uuid'. When using AgentDeploy, image_source is passed
to IPA in image_info dictionary in 'id' field without modification,
and IPA tries to download image to /tmp/{id} location. Deployment
fails as /tmp/glance://uuid is invalid location.

In this change image_source is split to ensure that uuid will be used
to name the file.

Closes-bug: #1400156
Change-Id: Id3658d2a32c87867d828bc3b3fecc94e514a4526

commit_message:
Hyper-V: attach volumes via SMB

Currently, the Hyper-V driver supports attaching volumes only via
iSCSI. This patch adds support for attaching volumes using VHD or
VHDX images hosted on SMB shares.

Note that the according Cinder drivers which allow exporting
images through SMB shares have been already merged.

The workflow is simple: using the connection info, the driver
chooses the right volume driver, mounts the according SMB share
using the according credentials. The only thing that needs to be
done next is actually attach the volume to an instance using its
UNC path.

Change-Id: Id5de0e6843c1035235598a4d72a00b7555187fb4
Implements: blueprint hyper-v-smbfs-volume-support

commit_message:
Split identity server into v2 and v3

We make the IdentityServer object an abstraction layer between v2 and v3
APIs as the whole object. By doing this we don't have to check at the
beginning of every function whether to use v2 or v3. This will be
important when using auth plugins because the expected workflow is just
to issue the calls and see which ones fail with EndpointNotFound and so
we would have to reorder the code to possibly issue each call twice.

We need the additional test discovery entries as discovery now happens
when you instantiate the IdentityServer object - not when you use it.
This will have no practical difference, it's just that in testing we
sometimes create the object to read values from it.

Change-Id: Ie05d99946c2b1127992cd9a083a2068a6e80398b

commit_message:
Libvirt: Fsfreeze during live-snapshot of qemu/kvm instances

Currently it is required to execute fsfreeze command manually before
taking snapshots of active instances, otherwise the snapshot may be
inconsistent. When qemu-guest-agent is installed in a kvm instance,
we can request the instance to fsfreeze via libvirt's fsFreeze API
which is introduced in libvirt 1.2.5. To utilize this feature,
the image metadata must have 'os_require_quiesce=yes' property.
'hw_qemu_guest_agent=yes' is also needed to enable qemu-guest-agent.

Implements: blueprint quiesced-image-snapshots-with-qemu-guest-agent
Change-Id: I137efe00839ae0cb35e142b0c8f8d75ae61cfb64
Signed-off-by: Tomoki Sekiyama <tomoki.sekiyama@hds.com>

commit_message:
VMware: allow selection of vSAN datastores

With support for handling of stream-optimized disk images added, the
vmware driver is now able to deploy to vSAN datastores, so add support
for the the 'vsan' datastore type, and update the datastore selection
logic to take this type into account when when spawning a
stream-optimized image.

Implements: blueprint vmware-vsan-support
Co-authored-by: Radoslav Gerganov <rgerganov@vmware.com>

Currently, in the ldap2py function, several fields are attempted

In doing so, an attempt to convert a field to int() is attempted,

'}]
commit_message:
User ids that begin with 0 cannot authenticate through ldap

Currently, in the ldap2py function, several fields are attempted
to be converted to python friendly types.

In doing so, an attempt to convert a field to int() is attempted,
but in some cases, a user id may begin with a 0. When the user
attempts to authenticate, they will be rejected since any additional
query will use the id without the 0 in front.

Closes-Bug: #1396763

Change-Id: I1e2436b845e534f6cdb0398b5cca17d8502b905f

commit_message:
Calculate rules_index after chain/rule processing

Currently rules_index may decremented if a duplicate rule or
chain is encountered that is not wrapped in the case of the
chain or in the case of a rule doesn't contain 'wrap_name'.
A duplicate rule/chain is a rule/chain that matches the above
criterea that iptables manager wants to add and that already
exists in the system's iptables ruleset.

Rather than deal with incrementing/decrementing the index when
a duplicate rule is encountered perhaps simpler alternative is
to not calculate the rule_index until the moment before the
new rules are inserted into the list of "new" rules.

The unit tests for this have been moved to the much better
written neutron.tests.unit.test_iptables_manager test.

Closes-Bug: 1311904
Change-Id: I9d88a4a8195f9f4a03bb8ba2accf2b9febeff42d

commit_message:
Incorrect work rally info find for SLA

If you type 'rally info find <query>' rally will suggest us docs that
 will be match by query. Even if you have one typo. otherwise it sugest
 you list of docs that you are possibly looking for. But if you type
'rally info find failure_rate' there output would be: "Failed to find
any docs for query: 'failure_rate'". Instead there must be information
about SLA(failure_rate): "Failure rate minimum and maximum in percents.".

Change-Id: Ie6c59e4091cddd8f5e81e2123cad1367b397a9b6
Closes-bug: 1399675

commit_message:
initialize objects with context in pci manager

These changes aim to clean up the pattern of passing a context in
object member functions create/destroy/refresh/save and instead
initialize the object with the context when it's constructed.

Change-Id: Ic860411f389b12d27b4a11cd15dfca6c11e55471

commit_message:
Print version info at start

When debugging problems from logs, it would be useful to know what
version is running across program start and stop.  In one case I have
a suspicion that an upgrade was run inbetween but the logs don't help
identify that.

My first thought was to grab this from argparse just as --version
does, but that's not really currently possible [1].

The original starting message is probably irrelevant, but I realise
log messages tend to suffer from Hotel California syndrome; you can
check-in but you can never leave.

[1] http://bugs.python.org/issue9399

Change-Id: Ia1bfd2f3589b508e19fd8a94d59beaafd6d657d2

commit_message:
Use condition variables using 'with'

Instead of doing [acquire, try, finally, release]
just use the condition variable as a context manager
to achieve the same effect with less code and with
less verbosity.

Change-Id: I0a3bb80a932a3dc6623ba2378afa0341e9e06e5a

commit_message:
Compute Add build_instance hook in compute manager

The build_instance hook provides a hook close to the actual spawn
of an instance. It distinguishes itself from the create_instance
hook because, in the case of a successful build, the instance will
exist on the hypervisor when the build_instance post hook is
called, instead of simply just being scheduled as is the case with
the create_instance post hook. This is useful as some details may
not be available until after scheduling.

Co-Authored-By: Corey Wright <corey.wright@rackspace.com>
Change-Id: Ic12abf6315bbc6b010b8222ef296ec65cb4b4f95

commit_message:
Inherit RequestContext from oslo

In the long-term, OpenStack projects should use oslo.context as the base
class for their custom contexts. This enables the use of
application-agnostic tools, e.g. global logging configurations. See
http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/oslo-specs/specs/juno/app-agnostic-logging-parameters.html

This patch syncs the latest context module from oslo-incubator and use
it as the base class for Cinder RequestContext. The goal is to clean up
Cinder code, and to be ready for the first oslo.context release.

Change-Id: Iba9354b402de556ca6e55e7c17dd6f3f1624d72d
Related-bug: #1210261

commit_message:
Fix timeout in test_slave_user_removed int-test

The test_slave_user_removed int-test polls to check that the
slave user account is removed, but doesn't currently have a time
out set. This means that a failure in this test causes the entire
suite to spin, and ultimately time out. Fix this by adding a 3 min
timeout to this test.

Change-Id: I5f869c7d3cb0587409b5a12a89ed673e57552b82
Closes-bug: 1399583

commit_message:
Obsolete oslo-incubator modules - importutils

This change is part of a multi-part change set to handle obsolete and
graduated oslo modules. This change addresses import utils that is now
part of oslo.utils.

The file importutils is not being deleted because of dependencies
within oslo-incubator

Partial-Bug: #1380789

commit_message:
Adds external attachment type validators to ML2

Adds external attachment type validator code for
binding ports with a HOST-ID field that represents
an L2 access point in a network (e.g. switch port + VLAN tag).

This will allow baremetal devices (e.g. Ironic servers) to be
attached to a given Neutron network via the standard ML2 port
binding mechanisms.

DocImpact

Partially Implements: blueprint neutron-external-attachment-points
Change-Id: I3a8472e3e7c990056f1f3846aadec40d70183661

commit_message:
Add API intercept to feed requests to handlers

Add an intercept layer to all requests for plugins via the neutron
manager. The interceptor passed back can then pass all requests through
intercept handlers. Each handler can modify the requets and results of
all method calls to core and service plugins.

Implements: blueprint api-intercept-plugin
Change-Id: Ia1dc1fdb2fdebd29e7a5546cf147323102f1bc28

commit_message:
Check the invalid suffix in RestAPI uri

Currently, RestAPI supports xml or json format type, invalid suffix
in uri should be forbidden.

Change-Id: I7e3c02e241d3993ca536876ace99187b2d2461e4
Closes-Bug: #1330095

Sync oslo-incubator

We hasn't synced with oslo-incubator in a while so this brings
us back up to date and updates neutron where needed.

Based from commit: 669f0383e933f5446427ed13341144e447fa5140

commit_message:
Implements: Brocade LBaaS Plugin Driver and Device Driver

Implementation of the blueprint neutron-brocade-lbaas-driver.
This patch set also supports simple file based device inventory.

Change-Id: I96eb443cf03b40171bef8580ae52a6837178e27f

commit_message:
Cisco N1KV: Enable HTTPs communication with VSM

Right now Cisco N1KV communicates with VSM using http.
This commit will make HTTPs the default communication of the plugin
and will also enable to configure that the plugin does SSL
verification of the VSM certificate.

The verification is optional since it needs an out of band
way to put the VSM certicate in the controller.

Change-Id: I863eb48c85c82126b7c9bb1e05f2bb4775ecb9d5
Closes-Bug: 1365600

This patch adds a drop rule after the dst: 127.0.0.1 port: 9697

commit_message:
Block external access directly to qg devices in logical routers.

The qg device in a logical router which has a gateway set
is accessible on that gateway's IP address. This is especially
problematic when the metadata-proxy is running as it becomes accessible.
This patch adds a drop rule after the dst: 127.0.0.1 port: 9697
rule for all traffic destined for the qg device which is not
RELATED,ESTABLISHED. Floating IP functionality happens prior to this
so that will continue working, and we really don't want anyone establishing
new connections into our logical routers directly.

Change-Id: Ica9b23490832c0b6037ebf84573a200d6c53d4ec
Closes-Bug: 1350975

commit_message:
Set default unit test timeout to 10 seconds

Set the default unit test timeout to 10 seconds instead
of having them run unbound. 10 seconds is more than long
enough to cover normal unit tests and will prevent changes
like Idd770a85a9eabff112d9613e75d8bb524020234a from merging,
which caused 2 seconds of tests to balloon up to 5 minutes.

Related-Bug: #1372076
Change-Id: I33a7334477172b98e9cf76e51cb958026221ba0f

commit_message:
Cisco DFA ML2 Mechanism Driver - part 2

This is part 2 of changes to support Cisco DFA ML2 mechanism driver.
The changes in this commit are in ovs_neutron_agent and they setup RPC for
Mechanism Driver.
In DFA topology where openstack compute nodes are connected to the external
switches or fabrics, VDP protocol is used to assign VLAN for communication
between VM on compute nodes and the switches. VDP is running on all compute
nodes and as part of the DFA requirements the VDP is required to send Cisco
organization-specific OUI to the switches. For that reason, the mechanism
driver prepares the data and send it to the agent on compute nodes using RPC.
The changes in this commit define parameters in the config file that both
mechanism driver and agent can use to setup RPC.
It is worth to note here that, RPC can be avoided if get_device_details could
ask a mechanism driver to add more information to the return dictionary if
they need to. For now this is not supported so RPC is used to exchange the
information.

Partially Implements: blueprint ml2-mechanism-driver-for-cisco-dfa

Change-Id: I56847b67f7be117b42896ddb41af95088acc245d

commit_message:
Implement ebtables manager

A manager for the ebtables utility. An ebtables manager
is needed for an additional patch, which will close an
ARP cache poisoning loophole.

While there are similarities between iptables-manager and
ebtables-manager, these have not been factored out, since
the iptables-manager code is sensitive and it's not
desirable to modify it at this time.

The implementation of the ebtables manager comes in large
part from an abandoned patch provided by Édouard Thuleau, which
he presented for review here:

        https://review.openstack.org/#/c/70067/

Credit for the workin of the ebtables manager should go to
Édouard, I merely ported it to today's code.

Related-bug: 1274034
Co-authored-by: Thuleau Édouard <edouard.thuleau@cloudwatt.com>

Change-Id: Ic3c92aed35bd7875c0bab25c95a9ca2e6b8ae243

commit_message:
Adds FWaaS service plugin for Cisco CSR1kv

Support for Cisco CSR1kv Firewall:
Add API extensions and associated db for insertion of FW service
on Cisco CSR1kv router. There are no changes to the reference implemention
model for FWaaS rules and policies.

Change-Id: I81c462211d9d42956783f432bfb5f9aef9021420
Implements: blueprint fwaas-cisco

commit_message:
LBaaS reference implementation driver to support TLS

Including plugin modifications for barbican container retrieval
Including template updates to support TLS and SNI
Including jinja_config updates to support storing of the container details
Including driver updates for data directory locations

Implement blueprint lbaas-ref-impl-tls-support

Change-Id: I47c34e7b8a0558373f3e3262a7c40ff43a367465

commit_message:
l3_db: refactor L3_NAT_dbonly_mixin add/remove_router_interface

This patch refactors add/remove_router_interface to allow
override actual port operation.
l3 plugin for routervm will twist port operation when
add/remove router interface as port creation/deletion will be
done with VM creation/deletion.
This patch simplifies vyatta vrouter patch.

Related to blueprint l3-plugin-brocade-vyatta-vrouter

Change-Id: Iaa69d835436c8f3c0fb70798ebf9c81f7727b0b2

commit_message:
External Attachment Point Extension

This introduces the external attachment point
extension API definition, DB classes, and mixin
class. It also loads the class in ML2 since this
is the target plugin with the port binding modulatirity
necessary to bind these ports.

Using this extension, administrators can define external
attachment strings to keep track of specific physical
ports in networks. These can then be assigned to tenants
who can then assign them to their own networks. An
assignment results in a port creation with the external
attachment identifier populated in the HOST ID field so
the plugin can bind the port to the network segment.

DocImpact

Implements: blueprint neutron-external-attachment-points
Change-Id: I51cc1c852f45d5f443ee0c0d1d1c6304a6d55992

commit_message:
BSN Plugin: external attachment support

Adds a Big Switch external attachment driver and support for
the external attachment point mixin to the Big Switch Plugin.
This allows arbitrary ports in the Big Switch fabric to be
connected to a Neutron network.

Implements: blueprint bsn-external-attachment

commit_message:
Fix the incorrect logic of _modify_rules()

Do not need to do 'rules_index -= 1', if one rule entry is removed
from new_filter. Need to do 'rules_index -= 1', if one chain entry
is removed from new_filter, because chain is above the rule.
Add one unit test for _modify_rules(), so that we will not make it
wrong in the future.

Change-Id: I00a1987d8ec6c1018bbc0e70e60dafbb13a0bd73
Closes-Bug: 1359072

commit_message:
Fix ovs agent fails to kill ovsdb monitor properly

_kill may be called by `_handle_process_error` or `stop` from outside,
if it is called more than once, following exception will occur:

AssertionError: Trying to re-send() an already-triggered event.

kill_event can't be re-used even if it is respawning, the patch
introduce a respawning state to indicate the process is respawning.

Change-Id: Id584b4444f5b65f0d532ccb930f70a08e5419c06
Closes-bug: #1350903

[{'number': 3, 'created': '2014-08-31 16:49:46.000000000', 'files': ['neutron/plugins/vmware/plugins/base.py'], 'message': 'Fixes port deletion failure if port missing in NVP

The issue here is that port deletion fails if the
port being deleted does not existing in the NSX
database. This does not necessarily mean that the
port does not exist entirely. Therefore, this fix
wraps the NSX port deletion around a try block that
ignores any failure. The port deletion fails only
if the port does not exist in the neutron database
as well.

commit_message:
Fixes port deletion failure if port missing in NVP

The issue here is that port deletion fails if the
port being deleted does not existing in the NSX
database. This does not necessarily mean that the
port does not exist entirely. Therefore, this fix
wraps the NSX port deletion around a try block that
ignores any failure. The port deletion fails only
if the port does not exist in the neutron database
as well.

Change-Id: Iaf3ff43b63bc321e29c86e6ce4704a5b2780ff16
Closes-Bug: 1293723

commit_message:
Handling exception on 504 Error

When load balancer/proxy return 504, client raises ValueError.
This happen when response is not a JSON object.
ValueError Exception is needed to be handled.

Change-Id: Iaa8d577f99137327f6e7ad9c7c6abc350f4cc938
Closes-Bug: #1358889

commit_message:
Add service group as a firewall customized service

This patch introduces the model and extension framework
for implementing service group as a firewall customized service.
Two resources service_group and service_object are added,
currently firewall rule can refer multiple service groups to allow the
user flexibilty to define their own groups and use them without impacting
the other users.
Each service object can be defined with a timeout value that can be used
to overwrite default session idle timeout value.
More info can be found at service group wiki
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron/FWaaS/FWaaS-ServiceGroup
Implements: blueprint fwaas-customized-service for customized service
Change-Id: If699bfd90f2a8d80ac93c51220707c856e94f8db
Authored-by: badveli vishnuvardhan <badveli_vishnuus@yahoo.com>

commit_message:
Implement bp/huawei-ml2-mechanism-driver

This driver proxy neutron request to huawei sdn controller
which can provide vxlan network provision. Huawei controller
can communicate with ovs based on openflow protocal, flow
table route info which can conduct vm traffic will be posted.

Implements: blueprint huawei-ml2-mechanism-driver
Change-Id: I6a4b59ab3bf5cc5a73cbb407f0cc4604407bc8f3

commit_message:
Implement Midonet Juno Port Api calls

This patch is part of a series of patches converting the current midonet plugin
code to the new model described in blueprint midonet-plugin-juno. This patch
focuses specifically on the "port" handlers.

Partially-Implements: blueprint midonet-plugin-juno
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

Change-Id: I3e5a87385d9e3f77d9f420a60338db224ce72964

commit_message:
Give floating IPs their own veth device

This way, floating IPs have their own MAC address, and additional
services or safeties can be applied to them. (think tcpdump) To
enable this feature, set floatingip_dedicated_device to True in
l3_agent.ini.

THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS

blueprint floatingip-dedicated-veth

Change-Id: I1914d9afdebfe71653cf958459fbfcd43c57bf8a

commit_message:
Fix ARP cache poisoning vulnerability

ARP cache poisoning is not actually prevented by the firewall
driver 'iptables_firewall'. We are using the ebtables manager
in order to create Ethernet frame filtering rules, which prevent
the sending of ARP cache poisoning frames.

Note:

    This commit is based entirely on Édouard Thuleau's patch, which
    he presented for review here:

        https://review.openstack.org/#/c/70067/

    His patch was abandoned. I have merely copied his code into the
    latest code base and made a few minor adjustments for this purpose.

    All credit for the patch should go to Édouard.

Change-Id: Iad9508862cdbd5a663027fa98d815b075e8ff833
Closes-Bug: 1274034

commit_message:
Avoid changing constants module when adding new service plugin

Loading a new service plugin requires changes to the:
neutron/plugins/common/constants.py

This patch adds an option to load this information as configuration. The
patch attempts to work within the current framework of extension and
service plugin configuration, and limit the scope of changes to those
minimally required to achieve this.

Change-Id: Ida49366e0047afeb7d96ebf7fceb9fb967d4c8a1
Closes-Bug: 1361813

commit_message:
ServiceInstanceInfo DB table

The table is part of the service insertion implementation.
The table is populated by each service plugin when a new instance
is created. When a new service_interface is created on a service
instance, the table is looked up to find the type of the service
for the instance.

Implements: blueprint service-base-class-and-insertion
Change-Id: Ie8015e16434445830b4df12a777f19e9fced391f

Service Insertion: Service Interface API and DB

This patch adds service interface API and DB. Service Interface
is a common interface definition for all advanced service to
manage insertion points to the network

Partially-implements: neutron-services-insertion-chaining-steering

commit_message:
Delete the port name from ovsdb when neutron port-delete is called

Until now, when a user deleted a port from the neutron client using
the port-delete command we didn't remove it from ovs-db port lists.
As a result of which the openvswitch agent didnt deleted the security
group rules for that port. This allowed us to ping to the affected VM
even when the port got delete resulting in a security threat.

Change-Id: Ifaeba4ab253288a341739497204c28c04ffc0847
Closes-Bug: #1333365

commit_message:
add routerport instead of overloading device_id

implements blueprint l3-router-port-relationship

Previously the l3_agent relied on overloading the device_id attribute to
link a port to a router. Overloading this attribute prevents using the
L3 extension in situations where the router might be a service VM (Nova
will not use a port that already has a device_id).

Change-Id: I23a3a45665db8f61ce94f624f52a019b89e51570

commit_message:
Support loading of service plugins via entrypoints

service_plugins are documented to use plain names that
are mapped via entrypoints to class names. However
neutron-db-manage was not handling this case.

Closes-Bug: #1286052
Change-Id: I3ce8e60d8b6ff4b471daf74dd05425edfc657fc0

commit_message:
Implement service vm framework: drivers for load balander (WIP)

This is work-in-progress yet. Only for early review/discussion.
This is just for showing its progress as early as possible and triggering
discussion based on the concrete code base.

A framework for for creating, managing and deploying Neutron advanced
services implemented as virtual machines.
The goal is to enable advanced network services (e.g. Load
Balancing, Security, Monitoring) that may be supplied by third party
vendors, are deployed as virtual machines, and are launched and
inserted into the tenant network on demand.

This is 1st phase:
two-leg VM for LBaaS service. VM effectively does nothing. Concept proofing.
As agreed at the design summit.

TODO:
done:- determine db model
done:- implement rest API
done:- python-neutron client
       https://github.com/yamahata/python-neutronclient.git adv-svc-vm
done:- talking nova with python-novaclient to spin up/down VM
done:- simple LBaaS driver (or apply this framework to existing LBaaS
  driver)
  done:- lbaas nova driver which requires trivial scheduler
done:- split patch into API/data model and lbaas part
done:- unit test for API/data model
done:- settle down management/data network/interface
WIP:- mgmt driver to communicate with hosting device and logical service
      instance
WIP:- mgmt driver for notifier api
WIP:- agent with notifier api
NEW:- unit test for simple lbaas driver
- devstack
  https://github.com/yamahata/devstack.git adv-svc-vm
- test
  - tempest?

- option: reference implementation of MGMT driver. SSH?
- option: use HEAT for spining up/down VM
- option: utlize l3-agent consolidation framework
- option: horizon GUI

etherpad
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/NeutronServiceVM

current status
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ZWDDTjwhIUedyipkDztM0_nBYgfCEP9Q77hhn1ZduCA/edit#heading=h.tajialn1fpoe

design overview
https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Ir8MZC7fJb8SOhiZOEQovP_EvdFz_cF_-GEWsidAu7k/edit?usp=sharing

Implement: blueprint adv-services-in-vms
---
Changes v12 -> 13:
- finished rest API/db model with unit test and split it out.

Change v11 -> v12:
- use six
- unit tests

Change v10 -> v11:
- simple driver for lbaas worked

Changes v9 -> v10:
- started mgmt driver
- started unit tests

Changes v8 -> v9:
- introduced driver for lbaas and simple scheduler (mostly done)
- started mgmt-if and networks.
  WIP. needs to be finished.

Changes v7 -> v8:
- use python-novaclient
- started lbaas driver

Changes v6 -> v7:
- nova driver tested
- reflected review(not all)

Changes v5 -> v6:
- added nova driver (not tested yet)
- use stevedore

Changes v4 -> v5:
- Rest API prototype
- python-neutron client

Changes v3 -> v4:
- fixed db table
- implemented basic db operations
- started REST API

Changes v2.1 -> v3
- more update on db tables.
- introduce vm/drivers dir

Changes v2 -> v2.1
- pep8
Changes v1 -> v2:
- reflected Bob's comment

Change-Id: Iede23f4199b4e027c7b28d7519fcccd69c37237d

commit_message:
Implement Midonet Juno Router Api calls

This patch is part of a series of patches converting the current midonet plugin
code to the new model described in blueprint midonet-plugin-juno. This patch
focuses specifically on the "router" handlers.

Partially-Implements: blueprint midonet-plugin-juno
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

Change-Id: I6457d2db09cc328196c587b7d1a8c29f6e86319e

commit_message:
Redact X-Auth-Token from http requests

X-Auth-Token is logged for every request which causes a lot
noise in nova logs and significantly increases its size -
instead of it log TOKEN_REDACTED like keystone client.
Closes-Bug: #1367339

Change-Id: I0a6884a49cc134d42747adbb20a28141dfd0aabc

commit_message:
Make neutronclient authenticate using keystoneclient

1. Delete user_id in command arguments.
2. Using keystoneclient to authenticate instead of using
   REST API request directly.
3. Using keystoneclient to authenticate will also let
   keystoneclient to log credentials. Hashing credentials
   in keystoneclient log will be fixed in Bug: 1004114.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib6151335cf0db7b4bd5546e81f56b6a20ef68bfd
Closes-Bug: 1327019
Co-authored-by: Xu Han Peng <xuhanp@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Add API in python-neutronclient for Cisco DFA

When creating a network in Cisco DFA topology, a new API is needed to return
list of supported configuration profiles.
This patch defines list_config_profiles API, which returns list of
available profiles stored in neutron database.

Change-Id: I7a0b8428248b5bda8bedcd59cc2633be3e868041
Implements: blueprint python-neutronclient-for-cisco-dfa

commit_message:
Use immutable arg rather mutable arg

Passing mutable objects as default args is a known Python pitfall.
We'd better avoid this. This commit changes mutable default args with
None.

commit_message:
Add service group as a firewall customized service

This patch introduces flexible way to allow user to specify more
than one type of traffic in the same rule.
two resources are added to enhance the FWaaS using the following cli
one is called service group and one is called service object
Administrator can use service object to define a special type of traffic.
The service objects is grouped into service group that can be referenced
from other openstack modules (eg. firewall rule).
New CLIs:
service-group-create
service-group-delete
service-group-list
service-group-show
service-group-update
service-object-create
service-object-delete
service-object-list
service-object-show
Implements: blueprint fwaas-customized-service for customized service
Change-Id: Ic1c05f94eb9b7cdab9472c43a2162acecf8c2d27
Authored-by: badveli vishnuvardhan <badveli_vishnuus@yahoo.com>

commit_message:

commit_message:
Expose retries and retry_interval

The python-neutronclient contains a connection retry logic, but it isn't
in use. "Maximum attempts reached" exception is raised after 1 attempt.

Solution:

    New constructor parameters: retries, retry_interval
    The retriable request will be retried 3 times
    The error message will contain the number of retries

Change-Id: I658b91c3275e8109ff9f504e969a0c8a61e9b091

commit_message:
Use timeutils.set_time_override instead of stubbing

Some old unit tests would stub timeutils.utcnow{,_ts} instead of
using the override functionality that timeutils has. This patch
makes all unit tests use the timeutils override in favor or stubbing
the functions out.

Change-Id: Ieca64e6e811970b252536049c51d53f528a27999

commit_message:
Don't look beyond subcommand for args to main

Don't pass arguments after the subcommand to the argument
parser for the main command. This will prevent collisions
between arguments that could share the same name with an
argument to the parent command (e.g. --timeout).

Closes-Bug: #1353536
Change-Id: I6c7d165f4428f38c03134ab77ae2b1a0b80fb00c

commit_message:
Added --source-port-range-min, --source-port-range-max

Partially-implements: blueprint ovs-firewall-driver

python-neutronclient users can already specify --port-range-min and
--port-range-max with security-group-rule-create to create a security
group rule with destination ports. This change allows users to
optionally specify --source-port-range-min and --source-port-range-max
with security-group-rule-create to create a security group rule that
will match on source ports.

Change-Id: Idcbd93912aed3d58573cc54b7ae598583b6bd8bd

commit_message:
Client support for group-based-policy-abstraction

Implement the CLI support for group-based-policy-abstraction. group-policy
adds resources such as endpoint, endpoint-group, contracts and policy-rules
to enable the specification of application requirements for both an app
provider and an app consumer.

commit_message:
Generic DNS Subsystem

This blueprint describes a generic DNS subsystem, which provides a basic DNS resolving service and the ability to communicate within a tenant or outside the cloud using fully qualified domain names. In addition, it provides an ability to add a pluggable DNS service provider.

See also: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/dns-subsystem

Change-Id: I5c6ab0fe9fa6909ee23605f2dec4861c8bf8ab24

Link Aggregation for Ironic

Allow Ironic to configure link aggregation

Provide the ability to boot a bare metal node
using a resilient network pair of interfaces in
an arbitrarily degraded state.  Also, provide a
way to represent the link aggregate.

commit_message:
Add log translation hints for neutron

Current oslo libraries support translating log messages using different
translation domains and oslo would like to see hints in all of our code
by the end of juno. So neutron should handle the changes out over the
release.Relate info about log translation hints as follows:
    https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo/+spec/log-messages-translation-domain-rollout
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/70455

blueprint support-log-translation-hints

Change-Id: I7a44c0c525d700d4e6ad089e17fb1801fdf6f6d9

commit_message:
Action support for security group rule

Security Group is an widely used extension in the OpenStack.
The model is widely used and get familiar with many users.
Basically, the security group will only support ALLOW action
and it's limited.
In this blueprint, we are going to support more ACTIONS including DENY,
ALLOW_CONNECTION and APPLY_SERVICE. We will also
add new attributes for rule such as *priority*
in rule in order to support these attributes.

Change-Id: I01eac77d07972ec1c941d2fb8691beee0dab9c9a

[{'number': 8, 'created': '2014-06-05 16:36:16.000000000', 'files': ['specs/juno/bgpvpn.rst'], 'message': 'Neutron Extension for BGPVPN

The Blueprint defines a set of APIs required to interconnect a
OpenStack virtual-network with an l3-VPN network as defined by RFC4364
(BGP/MPLS Virtual Private Networks).
L3VPN network is widely used in industry especially for enterprise.
This extension will support eVPN based L2VPN which is also widely used.

Change-Id: I73900d0aa083daddc6bef940b1cb6c0945b8884a
'}]
commit_message:
Neutron Extension for BGPVPN

The Blueprint defines a set of APIs required to interconnect a
OpenStack virtual-network with an l3-VPN network as defined by RFC4364
(BGP/MPLS Virtual Private Networks).
L3VPN network is widely used in industry especially for enterprise.
This extension will support eVPN based L2VPN which is also widely used.

Change-Id: I73900d0aa083daddc6bef940b1cb6c0945b8884a

commit_message:
Add spec for ml2-mechanism-snmp-vlan

An ML2 plugin that dynamically implements VLAN-based tenant network
separation on switches that are configurable using SNMP. This blueprint
would extend Neutron's control of VLAN membership to any physical switch
that implements SNMP write access to the standard Q-BRIDGE-MIB.

Change-Id: Ie826a6164abe765af95d75627bb05b77359f3b6e

commit_message:
Publish L3 service capabilites to client

For short term, remove validation of enum attributes
and revise help messages to support providers that
may have different limits and defaults.

For the long term, allow provider based L3 services
to publish their capabilities to the the Neutron client
giving more accurate information for attributes,
resulting in a better end-user experience.

Change-Id: Ib61d68275c290f875150f6f54f186e3680c316d5

commit_message:
Raise exception if invalid IP is specified

This patch ensures that all values specified for the configuration
option netapp_controller_ips are valid, rather than logging and
continuing with only the valid addresses.

commit_message:
Check for all required variables in keystone start.sh

This allows Kubernetes to reschedule the container in case a required
variable is missing, for example when the Kubernetes pod is started
before the service.

Additionally, define the KEYSTONE_ADMIN_SERVICE_HOST and
KEYSTONE_PUBLIC_SERVICE_HOST variables to their common version if not
already set to allow usage outside of Kubernetes with docker link
feature.

Change-Id: Ie0966c18076a770e4031bbf5f777dd1be0ba20bc
Closes-Bug: 1398632

NetApp fix vol migration unusability

in which the volume became unusable after successfull inbound
migration due to volume id usage instead of name_id.

Closes-bug: #1370098

commit_message:
Fix 3PAR driver attach error when host name missing

In some cases an error was being thrown by the 3PAR driver
when the 'name' property returned from queryHost was
missing.  This change adds a check so that the driver
reacts properly when this occurs.  Also removed an unneeded
warning output that was still in the FC driver.

This patch is related to this merged bug fix:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/138212/

Closes-Bug: 1398206
Change-Id: I6593dc68616f55496c42d625968adfc684f98032

commit_message:
Update LVM lockfile name identical to RAW and Qcow

Currently Raw and Qcow2 use filename as lock file identity
while LVM use whole path. This patch change the lockfile
name of LVM to identical to the others.
It will be helpful to allow driver layer code to remove
those files when the life cycle of an instance ends.

Related-Bug: #1256306

Change-Id: I07aa54032026ca479fe8de08308dae51527a6b13

commit_message:
Fixed row deletion for deleted stack

Now heat returns stack with "stack_status == 'DELETE_COMPLETE'"
for deleted stack. Added corresponding check to ajax handler.

HTTPNotFound is not used anymore and deprecated. Removed except
block for it.

Added raise to generic "except Exception" block to prevent
internal errors inside horizon.

Change-Id: Ia9cfd975790872918ba25c347319003ddc3468fa
Closes-Bug: #1367758

commit_message:
Add ability to zfssa driver to create multiple initiator groups

Currently the zfssa driver only support one initiator group. This
is causing broken scsi devices when detaching volumes from instances.
This fix adds support for configuring multiple initiator groups.

Closes-Bug: #1378390
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib3262ebd40e9c2ff2f36d0a7b1b5b3506ed3acc1

commit_message:
tests: ignore editor backups when testing spec sections

The tests.test_titles.TestTitles.test_template test has a
check for the spec filename ending in '.rst', which will
raise errors any time an editor creates a backup file
eg 'foo~' or 'foo.bak'.  Ignore these obvious editor temp
files.

Change-Id: I692670cbb10bcdbb8569a59dd3ad90cf3f43ae4b

commit_message:
virt: switch get_available_resource to use VirtHostResources

Update the get_available_resource() method so that the dict
it returns is entirely replaced by a VirtHostResources instance.
The resource tracker is update to convert this back into the
traditional dict format. It is expected that when the resource
tracker is refactored it will be able to use the new object
more directly and avoid the intermediate dict.

Blueprint: virt-driver-get-available-resources-object
Change-Id: I2e9c3ec326029f2a8c87ee31164f67e47d49f5f3

commit_message:
virt: introduce VirtHostResources object

Extend nova.virt.hardware to provide a VirtHostResources
class. An instance of this class will be capable of
representing the set of resources available & allocated
on a hypervisor host. It is intended that an instance
of this class be returned by the get_available_resource
method instead of an undocumented dict()

Blueprint: virt-driver-get-available-resources-object
Change-Id: I27ed23c6a7671b9bf3257f2af4437974daa0b11a

VirtPCIAddressInfo classes. The VirtPCIDeviceInfo class provides
information about a single PCI device present on the host. It
references a VirtPCIAddressInfo class instance to provide the

commit_message:
virt: introduce VirtPCIDeviceInfo & VirtPCIAddressInfo classes

Extend nova.virt.hardware to provide the VirtPCIDeviceInfo and
VirtPCIAddressInfo classes. The VirtPCIDeviceInfo class provides
information about a single PCI device present on the host. It
references a VirtPCIAddressInfo class instance to provide the
address of the device. If the device is a virtual function,
it will also reference a second VirtPCIAddressInfo instance to
provide the address of the physical function.

Blueprint: virt-driver-get-available-resources-object
Change-Id: I27ed23c6a7671b9bf3257f2af4437974daa0b13a

commit_message:
Show up to 1 decimal place for instance detail RAM

The current instance details page rounds the amount of RAM to the
nearest integer, which at GB and TB levels does not provide enough
fidelity to be useful, this patch allows the page to display up to one
decimal place if it is required, by changing the filter applied in the
template from mbformat to mb_float_format.

Change-Id: Ida97e83285b64ac6b08260f78f31c69dc37009b0
Closes-Bug: 1384446

subject: Nova config should use NOVA_SERVICE_HOST
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 4146, 'name': 'Clark Boylan', 'email': 'cboylan@sapwetik.org', 'username': 'cboylan'}, {'_account_id': 9009, 'name': 'Red Hat CI', 'email': 'redhatci@redhat.com', 'username': 'redhatci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-10-28 16:32:10.000000000', 'files': ['lib/nova'], 'message': 'Nova config should use NOVA_SERVICE_HOST

Much of the Nova config was using SERVICE_HOST (and in one case HOST_IP)
for Nova config options that should be overrideable to
NOVA_SERVICE_HOST. Update lib/nova:create_nova_conf to use
NOVA_SERVICE_HOST in these cases.

This makes the nova config consistent with other services and allows for
more flexibility (like running nova control plane behind NATed floating
IPs).

Change-Id: I823d9b79c04526b053715cda32926e1cf343368d
'}]
commit_message:
Nova config should use NOVA_SERVICE_HOST

Much of the Nova config was using SERVICE_HOST (and in one case HOST_IP)
for Nova config options that should be overrideable to
NOVA_SERVICE_HOST. Update lib/nova:create_nova_conf to use
NOVA_SERVICE_HOST in these cases.

This makes the nova config consistent with other services and allows for
more flexibility (like running nova control plane behind NATed floating
IPs).

Change-Id: I823d9b79c04526b053715cda32926e1cf343368d

Allow keypair to be specified in environment

an environment variable, NOVACLIENT_DEFAULT_KEY_NAME,  rather

commit_message:
Fix For Bug #1233492 : "nova list doesn't work with tenant name, only tenant id"

After this bug fix, the nova list will work with tenant name and tenant id. Change done in python-novaclient.

nova --os-tenant-name admin list --tenant demo --all-tenants 1 - Will return servers list (similar to, when tenant-id is passed in place of tenant-name)

Closes Bug : 1233492

Change-Id: Ie5f6aae7be5d844a42506232214fedcd4b8427ca

commit_message:
Add username of the owner in nova list response

Currently nova list command does not show which user the particular
VM belong too. In enterprise deployments, knowing which user booted
the VM could be very useful for the cluster administrator.
This will save admin a lot of manual steps before knowing the owner
of the VM. In this blueprint, we plan to add an additional column
'username' to 'nova list' output which will facilitate cluster
maintenance for the administrator
command to use: nova list --show-owner

Implements blueprint username-in-nova-list-response

Change-Id: I63c19cb92f09d61e1e1e5da994b777fb44781a81

commit_message:
limit novaclient commands to those available

Currently, "nova help"  mixes end user and cloud operator commands.
This fix adds a string "Administrative command" in the description of
commands, which are admin specific, to make it more informative to the
user. By doing this, non-admin users will get to know that the admin
specific commands will not work for him/her.

Closes bug: #892067

Change-Id: I839108ab59446235f7c0323bd5d2407725038cbf

commit_message:
Nova scrub will delete everything under a tenant

When passed a tenant id, nova scrub is suppose to delete
all instances, networks, and secgroups related to that tenant.
Right now, it doesn't clear any instances and it often gets
hung up on deleting secgroups.

Nova scrub will now delete all networks, secgroups, and instances
underneath the specified tenant.

Change-Id: I0ad6aa46df0e7a6de85871876c0ba20efc53046e
Closes-Bug: #1280389
Related-Bug: #1351315
